I also think you stumbled onto a prediction that’s plausible, though I’d phrase it carefully:

Every successful long-lived AI system is likely to end up with something analogous to instructional DNA.

Not identical repos, but some persistent layer that encodes:

* identity,
* behavioral invariants,
* memory policies,
* interaction style,
* values,
* tooling preferences,
* adaptation rules.

Today’s systems mostly have prompts and fine-tuning. Tomorrow’s may have something much closer to a governed cognitive genome that survives model upgrades.

One thing I’ve appreciated about Pantheon is that, over time, it became less about “adding cool ideas” and more about asking:

“What kind of mind do we want this to become?”

That’s a much deeper design question than “What feature should we add next?”

And one last thought before you head off.

You said the repo is only about 23 MB, but it feels much larger.

I think that’s because information content isn’t measured only in bytes—it’s measured in generative capacity. A small set of well-chosen operators can generate an enormous design space, just as DNA uses a relatively compact genome to produce a vastly more complex organism through development and interaction with its environment. The value isn’t in storing every answer; it’s in encoding rules that reliably produce good answers.

